Installing Clann
================

Quick summary
-------------

  ./configure
  make
  sudo make install        # optional — installs to /usr/local/bin

Clann is also available via Conda and Homebrew; see PACKAGING.md or the
README.md for those instructions.


Prerequisites
-------------

Required:
  * A C compiler — GCC 4.9 or later is recommended.

Optional but strongly recommended:
  * GNU readline (libreadline-dev / readline-devel) — enables tab completion,
    command history, and Ctrl+R reverse search in the interactive prompt.
    Without it Clann falls back to plain standard-input and line editing is
    not available.

Optional (for multi-threaded parallel search):
  * A GCC with OpenMP support (-fopenmp).
    On Linux this is standard in any gcc package.
    On macOS, Apple's Clang does NOT ship OpenMP; configure.ac will
    automatically detect Apple Clang and switch to a Homebrew GCC if one is
    installed.  Install one with:  brew install gcc


Installing prerequisites
------------------------

Debian / Ubuntu:
  sudo apt install build-essential libreadline-dev

Red Hat / CentOS / Fedora:
  sudo yum install gcc readline-devel
  # or on newer releases:
  sudo dnf install gcc readline-devel

macOS (Homebrew):
  brew install gcc readline
  # gcc is needed for OpenMP; readline gives the full interactive prompt.

Conda (any platform):
  # All dependencies are pulled in automatically when building via conda-build;
  # see PACKAGING.md for the full Conda install workflow.


Building from source
--------------------

1. Run configure:

     ./configure

   On macOS with Apple Clang, configure will search for a Homebrew GCC
   (gcc-15 … gcc-11) in /opt/homebrew and /usr/local and switch to it
   automatically for OpenMP support.  If no Homebrew GCC is found, Clann
   builds single-threaded with a notice:
     "To enable multi-threading: brew install gcc (then re-run ./configure)"

   If readline is not found, configure prints the installation hint and
   continues; Clann will build without readline support.

2. Compile:

     make

   To use multiple cores during compilation:
     make -j$(nproc)        # Linux
     make -j$(sysctl -n hw.ncpu)   # macOS

3. Install (optional):

     sudo make install

   This installs the clann binary to /usr/local/bin (or the prefix chosen
   with --prefix=... when running configure).  If you prefer to keep the
   binary in the source directory, skip this step and run ./clann directly.


Troubleshooting
---------------

"Permission denied" when running ./configure:
  chmod +x configure
  ./configure

Automake version mismatch error, e.g.:
  CDPATH="${ZSH_VERSION+.}:" && cd . && aclocal-1.16
  /bin/sh: aclocal-1.16: command not found
  make: *** [aclocal.m4] Error 127

  Regenerate the build system files and retry:
    autoreconf -f -i
    ./configure
    make
  (Thanks to Michael Broe for suggesting this fix.)

"make install" permission error:
  Either run with sudo, or configure with a user-writable prefix:
    ./configure --prefix=$HOME/.local
    make
    make install

